<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>

<head>
  <style>
    @page {
      size: A4;
      margin: 20mm;
    }

    body {
      font-family: {{customization.fontFamily}};
      color: #333;
      line-height: 1.7;
    }

    .header {
      text-align: center;
      margin-bottom: 25px;
      padding-bottom: 15px;
      border-bottom: 3px solid {{customization.primaryColor}};
    }

    .title {
      font-size: 32px;
      color: {{customization.primaryColor}};
      margin: 0;
    }

    .icon {
      font-size: 50px;
      margin-bottom: 10px;
    }

    .intro-text {
      font-size: 14px;
      margin-bottom: 20px;
    }

    .timeline {
      position: relative;
      margin: 25px 0;
    }

    .timeline::before {
      content: '';
      position: absolute;
      left: 50px;
      top: 0;
      bottom: 0;
      width: 3px;
      background: linear-gradient(to bottom, {{customization.primaryColor}}, {{customization.secondaryColor}});
    }

    .milestone {
      display: flex;
      align-items: flex-start;
      margin: 15px 0;
      position: relative;
    }

    .age-badge {
      width: 70px;
      height: 70px;
      background: {{customization.primaryColor}};
      color: white;
      border-radius: 50%;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      font-weight: bold;
      flex-shrink: 0;
      margin-right: 20px;
      position: relative;
      z-index: 1;
    }

    .age-badge .number {
      font-size: 22px;
      line-height: 1;
    }

    .age-badge .label {
      font-size: 9px;
      text-transform: uppercase;
    }

    .milestone-content {
      flex: 1;
      background: #FAFAFA;
      padding: 15px;
      border-radius: 10px;
      border-left: 3px solid {{customization.primaryColor}};
    }

    .milestone-title {
      font-size: 16px;
      font-weight: bold;
      color: {{customization.primaryColor}};
      margin-bottom: 6px;
    }

    .milestone-content p {
      font-size: 13px;
      margin: 0;
      color: #555;
    }

    .brain-box {
      background: linear-gradient(135deg, #E8F4FD 0%, #F0E8FD 100%);
      padding: 20px;
      border-radius: 12px;
      margin: 25px 0;
    }

    .brain-box h3 {
      font-size: 16px;
      color: {{customization.primaryColor}};
      margin: 0 0 12px 0;
    }

    .brain-box p {
      font-size: 13px;
      margin: 0 0 10px 0;
    }

    .brain-box p:last-child {
      margin: 0;
    }

    .tip-box {
      background: #FFF8E7;
      border: 2px dashed {{customization.primaryColor}};
      padding: 15px;
      border-radius: 10px;
      margin-top: 20px;
    }

    .tip-box p {
      font-size: 14px;
      margin: 0;
      text-align: center;
    }

    .tip-box strong {
      color: {{customization.primaryColor}};
    }
  </style>
</head>

<body>
  <div class="header">
    <div class="icon">üìÖ</div>
    <h1 class="title">When to Start & What to Expect</h1>
  </div>

  <div class="intro-text">
    <p>Even in the womb, your baby begins recognizing your voice and the patterns of your language. From birth, they can distinguish your native language from others! Understanding your baby's developmental journey helps you know when and how to introduce signs.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="timeline">
    <div class="milestone">
      <div class="age-badge">
        <span class="number">0-6</span>
        <span class="label">months</span>
      </div>
      <div class="milestone-content">
        <div class="milestone-title">The Watching Phase</div>
        <p>During this stage, crying is your baby's main communication tool. They're absorbing everything‚Äîyour voice, your expressions, your gestures. You can start signing now; your baby is watching and learning even if they can't respond yet.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="milestone">
      <div class="age-badge">
        <span class="number">6-8</span>
        <span class="label">months</span>
      </div>
      <div class="milestone-content">
        <div class="milestone-title">Communicative Intent Emerges</div>
        <p>A breakthrough moment! Your baby develops a strong urge to communicate. You'll notice them pointing, reaching, and making sounds with purpose. This is the ideal time to introduce signs consistently. They may naturally develop gestures like raising arms to be picked up.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="milestone">
      <div class="age-badge">
        <span class="number">8-12</span>
        <span class="label">months</span>
      </div>
      <div class="milestone-content">
        <div class="milestone-title">First Signs Appear</div>
        <p>Most babies produce their first intentional sign during this window. It might look a little different from yours‚Äîthat's completely normal! The motor skills for precise hand movements are still developing. Celebrate every attempt!</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="milestone">
      <div class="age-badge">
        <span class="number">12-18</span>
        <span class="label">months</span>
      </div>
      <div class="milestone-content">
        <div class="milestone-title">The Sign Explosion</div>
        <p>Once your baby masters a few signs, learning accelerates rapidly. Many babies learn 10-20+ signs during this exciting period. They'll start combining signs and using them spontaneously throughout the day.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="milestone">
      <div class="age-badge">
        <span class="number">18-24</span>
        <span class="label">months</span>
      </div>
      <div class="milestone-content">
        <div class="milestone-title">Bridge to Speech</div>
        <p>As verbal skills develop, your child will naturally start replacing signs with words. Keep signing! Even when they say a word, they may not pronounce it clearly yet. Signs remain a helpful backup that prevents frustration.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="brain-box">
    <h3>üß† What's Happening in Your Baby's Brain</h3>
    <p>When you speak a word AND show a sign, your baby's brain lights up in multiple areas: the <strong>auditory cortex</strong> processes the sound, the <strong>visual cortex</strong> processes what they see, and when they sign back, the <strong>motor cortex</strong> gets involved too.</p>
    <p>This multi-sensory experience creates stronger, more interconnected neural pathways. That's why signing babies often remember words more easily‚Äîthey've stored them in multiple places in their brain!</p>
  </div>

  <div class="tip-box">
    <p>‚è∞ <strong>Remember:</strong> It's never too early or too late to start! Whether you begin at 4 months or 14 months, what matters most is consistency, patience, and making it fun.</p>
  </div>
</body>

</html>
